    {
      "@id": "asbval:assertion/card/task_005/scope_drift",
      "@type": "asbval:ScopeDriftAssertion",
      "asbval:drift_notes": [
        "The card title refers to a 'modular peak-picking dispatch layer' which is somewhat overstated. The paper describes LipidMatch as accepting feature tables from multiple peak-picking tools (MZmine, XCMS, MS-DIAL) but does not detail a sophisticated dispatch mechanism\u2014rather, it simply accepts CSV-formatted feature tables from any of these sources.",
        "Compound Discoverer is mischaracterized in the card as a peak-picking tool. The paper uses it for post-identification appending of metabolite/xenobiotic annotations, not as a source of peak-picking input to LipidMatch.",
        "The research question focuses narrowly on MZmine conversion, but the paper emphasizes that LipidMatch accepts feature tables from multiple peak-picking tools with flexible input formats, not a MZmine-specific conversion pipeline."
      ],
      "asbval:n_drift_notes": 3,
      "asbval:target_artifact_id": "task_005",
      "asbval:target_artifact_kind": "card",
      "prov:wasAttributedTo": "anthropic/claude-haiku-4-5-20251001",
      "prov:wasGeneratedAtTime": "2026-06-16T06:08:56.550276+00:00",
      "sepio:credibility_status": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/SEPIO_0000339"
      }
    },
    {
      "@id": "asbval:assertion/skill/acquisition-mode-enumeration-and-validation/000",
      "@type": "asbval:ClaimAssessment",
      "asbval:evidence_quote": "LipidMatch was developed and tested using data acquired from a Q-Exactive orbitrap mass spectrometer (Thermo Scientific, San Jose, CA). LipidMatch has also been tested using data acquired on an Agilent 6540 Q-TOF (Agilent Technologies, Santa Clara, CA). LipidMatch can be used with a variety of other vendors and data formats. Ion selection techniques used to acquire fragmentation, including all-ion-fragmentation (AIF), inclusion list-based targeted approaches, and data-dependent topN (ddMS2-topN) approaches can be used with LipidMatch to annotate lipids acquired using liquid chromatography, direct injection, or imaging approaches. LipidMatch is not recommended for most applications using low resolution mass spectrometers.",
      "asbval:note": "Paper documents validated platforms (Q-Exactive orbitrap, Agilent 6540 Q-TOF) and acquisition modes (AIF, targeted, ddMS2-topN, LC, direct injection, imaging), but does NOT enumerate a complete matrix with explicit negative cases for all vendor/platform combinations. The claim of 'complete matrix' and 'explicit negative cases' is overstated; the paper provides selective validation examples and one negative case (low-resolution MS not recommended) but not a systematic enumeration.",
      "asbval:perspicacite_kb": "asb-paper-10-1186-s12859-017-1744-3",
      "asbval:supported_raw": "partial",
      "asbval:target_artifact_id": "acquisition-mode-enumeration-and-validation",
      "asbval:target_artifact_kind": "skill_bundle",
      "asbval:target_claim_field": "research_question",
      "asbval:target_claim_text": "Systematically enumerate and document the complete matrix of instrument platforms, vendors, and acquisition modes for which a lipidomics software tool (LipidMatch) has been validated, including explicit negative cases.",
      "eco:evidence_type": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/ECO_0000361"
      },
      "prov:wasAttributedTo": "anthropic/claude-haiku-4-5-20251001",
      "prov:wasGeneratedAtTime": "2026-06-16T06:10:54.441871+00:00",
      "sepio:credibility_status": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/SEPIO_0000339"
      }
    },
    {
      "@id": "asbval:assertion/skill/acquisition-mode-enumeration-and-validation/001",
      "@type": "asbval:ClaimAssessment",
      "asbval:evidence_quote": "We introduce LipidMatch, an R-based tool for lipid identification for liquid chromatography tandem mass spectrometry workflows. For each MS/MS scan of each feature, experimental fragments are matched against in silico lipid fragments m/z using a tolerance window (ppm).",
      "asbval:note": "LipidMatch is confirmed as the primary tool; fragment matching mechanism is explicitly described.",
      "asbval:perspicacite_kb": "asb-paper-10-1186-s12859-017-1744-3",
      "asbval:supported_raw": "yes",
      "asbval:target_artifact_id": "acquisition-mode-enumeration-and-validation",
      "asbval:target_artifact_kind": "skill_bundle",
      "asbval:target_claim_field": "tools[0]",
      "asbval:target_claim_text": "LipidMatch - Target tool for which compatibility matrix is constructed; performs lipid identification via matching experimental and simulated fragment m/z values",
      "eco:evidence_type": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/ECO_0000033"
      },
      "prov:wasAttributedTo": "anthropic/claude-haiku-4-5-20251001",
      "prov:wasGeneratedAtTime": "2026-06-16T06:10:54.441871+00:00",
      "sepio:credibility_status": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/SEPIO_0000338"
      }
    },
    {
      "@id": "asbval:assertion/skill/acquisition-mode-enumeration-and-validation/002",
      "@type": "asbval:ClaimAssessment",
      "asbval:evidence_quote": "LipidMatch was developed and tested using data acquired from a Q-Exactive orbitrap mass spectrometer (Thermo Scientific, San Jose, CA). Ion selection techniques used to acquire fragmentation, including all-ion-fragmentation (AIF), inclusion list-based targeted approaches, and data-dependent topN (ddMS2-topN) approaches can be used with LipidMatch.",
      "asbval:note": "Q-Exactive orbitrap is explicitly named as a tested platform; AIF, targeted, and ddMS2-topN modes are all mentioned as compatible.",
