      }
    },
    {
      "@id": "asbval:assertion/skill/batch-script-execution-and-automation/006",
      "@type": "asbval:ClaimAssessment",
      "asbval:evidence_quote": "Video tutorial 2 explains how users can process data using MSConvert and MZmine 2.20 using a batch file for MZmine. The batch file was optimized for lipids using the chromatographic methods in Additional file 2: Table S2 and is included with the tutorial videos in the LipidMatch file. Once feature tables are created for each biological substrate and each polarity, features can be directly annotated using LipidMatch and the previously generated MS/MS data.",
      "asbval:note": "Paper confirms batch file execution for MZmine and feature table generation, but the scope description overstates the automation. The paper describes batch file use for MZmine processing and MSConvert conversion, but does not describe automated conversion scripts that transform peak-picking output into LipidMatch format. Rather, users manually place feature tables in directories with specific naming conventions (.csv files ending in 'n.csv', 'neg.csv', 'p.csv', or 'pos.csv').",
      "asbval:perspicacite_kb": "asb-paper-10-1186-s12859-017-1744-3",
      "asbval:supported_raw": "partial",
      "asbval:target_artifact_id": "batch-script-execution-and-automation",
      "asbval:target_artifact_kind": "skill_bundle",
      "asbval:target_claim_field": "scope",
      "asbval:target_claim_text": "batch-script-execution-and-automation for transforming peak-picking software output into LipidMatch-compatible input format",
      "eco:evidence_type": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/ECO_0000361"
      },
      "prov:wasAttributedTo": "anthropic/claude-haiku-4-5-20251001",
      "prov:wasGeneratedAtTime": "2026-06-16T06:11:11.248610+00:00",
      "sepio:credibility_status": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/SEPIO_0000339"
      }
    },
    {
      "@id": "asbval:assertion/skill/batch-script-execution-and-automation/007",
      "@type": "asbval:ClaimAssessment",
      "asbval:evidence_quote": "The feature table can have nearly any format, allowing flexibility in choosing feature processing workflows. Video tutorial 2 explains how users can process data using MSConvert and MZmine 2.20 using a batch file for MZmine. Once feature tables are created for each biological substrate and each polarity, features can be directly annotated using LipidMatch and the previously generated MS/MS data.",
      "asbval:note": "Paper confirms that feature tables from MZmine, XCMS, MS-DIAL can be used as input. However, Compound Discoverer is not described as a source of peak-picking feature tables for LipidMatch input; it is only mentioned as a tool for appending identifications post-analysis.",
      "asbval:perspicacite_kb": "asb-paper-10-1186-s12859-017-1744-3",
      "asbval:supported_raw": "partial",
      "asbval:target_artifact_id": "batch-script-execution-and-automation",
      "asbval:target_artifact_kind": "skill_bundle",
      "asbval:target_claim_field": "scope - inputs",
      "asbval:target_claim_text": "peak table or feature list output file from MZmine, XCMS, MS-DIAL, or Compound Discoverer in native export format",
      "eco:evidence_type": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/ECO_0000361"
      },
      "prov:wasAttributedTo": "anthropic/claude-haiku-4-5-20251001",
      "prov:wasGeneratedAtTime": "2026-06-16T06:11:11.248610+00:00",
      "sepio:credibility_status": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/SEPIO_0000339"
      }
    },
    {
      "@id": "asbval:assertion/skill/batch-script-execution-and-automation/008",
      "@type": "asbval:ClaimAssessment",
      "asbval:evidence_quote": "The feature table can have nearly any format, allowing flexibility in choosing feature processing workflows. Each folder should contain respective MS/MS data for that substrate in .ms2 format also ending in 'neg.csv' or 'pos.csv', depending on polarity. Feature table(s) and MS/MS data are placed into a directory as shown in Fig. 2.",
      "asbval:note": "Paper indicates that feature tables are placed in directories with specific naming conventions, but does not explicitly describe a conversion process that outputs a 'mapped' file with specific column names. The paper states 'The feature table can have nearly any format', suggesting minimal transformation is required rather than active column mapping.",
      "asbval:perspicacite_kb": "asb-paper-10-1186-s12859-017-1744-3",
      "asbval:supported_raw": "partial",
      "asbval:target_artifact_id": "batch-script-execution-and-automation",
      "asbval:target_artifact_kind": "skill_bundle",
      "asbval:target_claim_field": "scope - outputs",
      "asbval:target_claim_text": "LipidMatch-compatible input file with mapped columns (m/z, retention time, intensity)",
      "eco:evidence_type": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/ECO_0000361"
      },
      "prov:wasAttributedTo": "anthropic/claude-haiku-4-5-20251001",
      "prov:wasGeneratedAtTime": "2026-06-16T06:11:11.248610+00:00",
      "sepio:credibility_status": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/SEPIO_0000339"
      }
    },
    {
      "@id": "asbval:assertion/skill/csv-data-aggregation-and-deduplication/000",
      "@type": "asbval:ClaimAssessment",
      "asbval:evidence_quote": "LipidMatch in silico libraries were developed in Excel as described in video tutorial 6 in the Additional file 1. Briefly, an R script was used to generate a list of possible fatty acid combinations for acyl containing lipids with 2 or 3 fatty acids... LipidMatch currently contains the most comprehensive lipid fragmentation libraries of freely available software, when ranked by the number of lipid types. LipidMatch includes in silico libraries with over 250,000 lipid species across 56 lipid types",
      "asbval:note": "Paper describes LipidMatch library generation and composition (250,000+ species, 56 types) but does NOT describe a task of loading/parsing multiple .csv files to aggregate and deduplicate them for validation. The paper describes library CREATION and VALIDATION by developers, not a user-facing workflow for verifying library completeness post-download. The card conflates library development (internal to LipidMatch) with a user task (external validation).",
      "asbval:perspicacite_kb": "asb-paper-10-1186-s12859-017-1744-3",
      "asbval:supported_raw": "partial",
      "asbval:target_artifact_id": "csv-data-aggregation-and-deduplication",
      "asbval:target_artifact_kind": "skill_bundle",
      "asbval:target_claim_field": "research_question",
      "asbval:target_claim_text": "Load and parse multiple .csv library files, extract species identifiers and category assignments, aggregate distinct entries using set operations, and enumerate unique categories to verify library completeness.",
      "eco:evidence_type": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/ECO_0000361"
      },
      "prov:wasAttributedTo": "anthropic/claude-haiku-4-5-20251001",
      "prov:wasGeneratedAtTime": "2026-06-16T06:11:33.080016+00:00",
      "sepio:credibility_status": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/SEPIO_0000339"
      }
    },
    {
      "@id": "asbval:assertion/skill/csv-data-aggregation-and-deduplication/001",
      "@type": "asbval:ClaimAssessment",
      "asbval:evidence_quote": null,
      "asbval:note": "Paper does not describe a user workflow for downloading and validating LipidMatch libraries post-hoc. LipidMatch libraries are static .csv files distributed with the software; the paper describes internal validation during development (using internal standards, literature, MS/MS databases) but not a user-facing aggregation/deduplication task. The 250,000 species and 56 types are fixed library properties, not user-computed thresholds.",
      "asbval:perspicacite_kb": "asb-paper-10-1186-s12859-017-1744-3",
      "asbval:supported_raw": "no",
      "asbval:target_artifact_id": "csv-data-aggregation-and-deduplication",
      "asbval:target_artifact_kind": "skill_bundle",
      "asbval:target_claim_field": "scope",
      "asbval:target_claim_text": "When you have downloaded a multi-file .csv library repository (e.g., LipidMatch) and need to verify that it meets minimum thresholds for species diversity (e.g., 500,000+ distinct lipid species) and category breadth (e.g., 60+ lipid-type categories).",
      "eco:evidence_type": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/ECO_0007675"
      },
      "prov:wasAttributedTo": "anthropic/claude-haiku-4-5-20251001",
      "prov:wasGeneratedAtTime": "2026-06-16T06:11:33.080016+00:00",
      "sepio:credibility_status": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/SEPIO_0000340"
      }
    },
    {
      "@id": "asbval:assertion/skill/csv-data-aggregation-and-deduplication/002",
      "@type": "asbval:ClaimAssessment",
      "asbval:evidence_quote": "[SUBSTRING-MATCH for LipidMatch | role: in-silico fragmentation library source] LipidMatch currently has over 250,000 lipid species spanning 56 lipid types contained in in silico fragmentation libraries.",
      "asbval:note": "LipidMatch does contain .csv library files (confirmed: 'LipidMatch in silico libraries were developed in Excel' and distributed as .csv format per passage 4). However, the paper does not describe a user task of aggregating/deduplicating multiple LipidMatch .csv files. LipidMatch libraries are pre-aggregated and static; users select which lipid types to query, not aggregate multiple library files.",
      "asbval:perspicacite_kb": "asb-paper-10-1186-s12859-017-1744-3",
      "asbval:supported_raw": "partial",
      "asbval:target_artifact_id": "csv-data-aggregation-and-deduplication",
      "asbval:target_artifact_kind": "skill_bundle",
      "asbval:target_claim_field": "tools[0]",
      "asbval:target_claim_text": "LipidMatch (in-silico fragmentation library source; contains .csv library files to be aggregated and deduplicated)",
      "eco:evidence_type": {
